    <p style="font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Percentages mask reality.</strong> Malawi has the highest overstay rate at a staggering 22.45%, which looks alarming on paper. However, that translates to just 504 people. Meanwhile, Nigeria has a relatively &#8220;safe&#8221; overstay rate of just 5.56%, but due to sheer volume, this accounts for 6,917 people—more than the next ten countries combined. When policymakers use <em>rates</em> to trigger visa restrictions, they often penalize smaller nations with negligible actual impacts on US immigration systems.</p>
